{"title_page": "Women in Turkish politics", "text_new": "{{Women in Turkey}}\n\n[[Women in Turkey]] have an active participation in national politics, and the number of women in the [[Turkish parliament]] has been increasing steadily in recent elections.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Hat\u0131 \u00c7\u0131rpan.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Hat\u0131 \u00c7\u0131rpan]], one of the first women in the Parliament of Turkey, 1935.]]\nThe [[Republic of Turkey]] was founded on the ashes of the [[Ottoman Empire]] on 29 October 1923. Although the political power of some [[Valide Sultan]]s (queen mothers) over the [[Ottoman Sultans]] was considerable, especially during the era known as the [[Sultanate of Women]], women had no chance to serve in any official political post in the Ottoman era.\n\nOne notable female political activist in the first days of the Republican era was [[Nezihe Muhittin]], who founded the first women's party in Turkey in June 1923; however, it was never legalized because the Republic was not officially declared yet. [[Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]], the founder of the Republic initiated a [[Atat\u00fcrk's Reforms|series of reforms]] to modernize the country, including civil and political equality for women for the first time. On 17 February 1926, Turkey adopted a new [[Turkish civil code (1926)|civil code]] by which the rights of Turkish women and men were declared equal except in suffrage.<ref>Sina Ak\u015fin:''K\u0131sa T\u00fcrkiye Tarihi'', T\u00fcrkiye \u0130\u015f bankas\u0131 K\u00fclt\u00fcr yay\u0131nlar\u0131,\u0130stanbul,2011,{{ISBN|978-9944-88-172-2}} p.188.</ref> After a short but intense struggle, Turkish women achieved voting rights in local elections by Act no. 1580 on 3 April 1930.<ref name=\"tempo\">''T\u00fcrkiye'nin 75 y\u0131l\u0131'' , Tempo Yay\u0131nc\u0131l\u0131k, \u0130stanbul, 1998, p.48,59,250</ref> Four years later, through legislation enacted on 5 December 1934, they gained full universal suffrage, earlier than most other countries.<ref name=\"tempo\"/>\n\n== President ==\nUp to the present, there have been no female [[President of Turkey|Presidents]] in Turkey.\n\n== Speakers of Parliament ==\nUp to the present, there have been no female [[Speaker of the Grand National Assembly|Speakers of Grand National Assembly]] in Turkey.\n\n== Vice President ==\nUp to the present, there have been no female [[Vice President of Turkey|Vice Presidents]] in Turkey.\n\nVice President office established in Turkey in 2018.\n\n== Prime Minister (1923-2018) ==\n[[File:(Tansu \u00c7iller) Rueda de prensa de Felipe Gonz\u00e1lez y la primera ministra de Turqu\u00eda. Pool Moncloa. 16 de noviembre de 1995 (cropped).jpeg|thumb|upright|[[Tansu \u00c7iller]] is first and only female [[Prime Minister of Turkey|Prime Minister]] of [[Turkey]].]]\n[[Tansu \u00c7iller]], a career professor of economics since 1983, entered politics in November 1990, joining the conservative [[True Path Party]] (DYP). On June 13, 1993, she was elected the party's leader, and on 25 June the same year, \u00c7iller was appointed the [[Prime Minister of Turkey|Prime Minister]] of a coalition government, becoming Turkey's first and only female prime minister to date. She served at this post until 6 March 1996.\n\nPrime Minister office abolished in Turkey in 2018.\n\n==Government ministers==\nThe first female Turkish [[Cabinet of Turkey|government minister]] was [[T\u00fcrk\u00e2n Akyol]], in 1971. She was the [[Ministry of Health (Turkey)|Minister of Health]] in [[Nihat Erim]]'s technocratic government.<ref name=\"75 y\u0131l\">''T\u00fcrkiye'nin 75 y\u0131l\u0131'', H\u00fcrg\u00fc\u00e7 Gazetecilik,, \u0130stanbul,1998</ref><ref name=\"h\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/16508594_p.asp |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet]] |title=Erkek egemen T\u00fcrkiye |date=2010-12-11 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref> In 1983, she was one of the founders of [[SODEP]], short for Social Democracy Party, a new party which went on to become one of the major political parties of Turkey in 1980s.\n\nFemale government ministers up to the present are as follows:\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!Name\n!Ministry\n!Party\n|-\n|[[T\u00fcrk\u00e2n Akyol]]<br />(1928\u20132017)||[[Ministry of Health (Turkey)|Minister of Health and Social Security]] (1971)<ref name=\"75 y\u0131l\"/><br />Minister of State (Family) 1992\u20131993|| (''[[Independent politician|independent]]'')<br />[[Social Democratic Populist Party (Turkey)|SHP]]\n|-\n|[[Nermin Neft\u00e7i]]<br />(1924\u20132003)||[[Ministry of Culture and Tourism (Turkey)|Minister of Culture]] (1974\u20131975)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[Republican Reliance Party|CGP]]\n|-\n|[[\u0130mren Aykut]]<br />(born 1940)||[[Ministry of Family, Labour and Social Services (Turkey)|Minister of Labour and Social Security]] (1987\u20131991)<br /> Minister of State (1991 and 1996),<br />[[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)|Minister of Environment]] (1997\u20131999)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/ekonomi/19847923.asp |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet]] |title=Eski \u00c7al\u0131\u015fma Bakan\u0131\u2019n\u0131 bile \u2018ye\u015fil kart testi\u2019ne \u00e7a\u011f\u0131rd\u0131lar |author=Babacan, Nuray |date=2012-02-06 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref>||[[Motherland Party (Turkey)|ANAP]]\n|-\n| [[G\u00fcler \u0130leri]]<br />(born 1948)|| Minister of State (1991\u20131993)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[Social Democratic Populist Party (Turkey)|SHP]]\n|-\n| [[Aysel Baykal]]<br />(1939\u20132003)|| Minister of State (1995\u20131995)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tbmm.gov.tr/hukumetler/HB50.htm |publisher=TBMM |title=I. \u00c7iller H\u00fck\u00fcmeti Bakanlar Kurulu 25.06.1993\u201305.10.1995 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref>||[[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|CHP]]\n|-\n| [[\u00d6nay Alpago]]<br />(born 1947)|| Minister of State (1994\u20131995)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[Social Democratic Populist Party (Turkey)|SHP]]\n|-\n| [[I\u015f\u0131lay Sayg\u0131n]]<br />(1947-2019)|| Minister of State (1995\u20131996)<br /> [[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)|Minister of Environment]] (1996),<br /> [[Ministry of Culture and Tourism (Turkey)|Minister of Tourism]] (1996)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[True Path Party|DYP]]\n|-\n| [[Ayfer Y\u0131lmaz]]<br />(born 1956)|| Minister of State (1996\u20131997)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[True Path Party|DYP]]\n|-\n| [[Tansu \u00c7iller]]<br />(born 1946)||[[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] (1996\u20131997)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[True Path Party|DYP]]\n|-\n| [[Meral Ak\u015fener]]<br />(born 1956)||[[Ministry of the Interior (Turkey)|Minister of Interior]] (1996\u20131997)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[True Path Party|DYP]]\n|-\n| [[Tayyibe G\u00fclek]]<br />(born 1968)|| Minister of State (1999\u20132002)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[Democratic Left Party (Turkey)|DSP]]\n|-\n| [[Melda Bayer]]<br />(born 1950)|| Minister of State (1999\u20132002)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[Democratic Left Party (Turkey)|DSP]]\n|-\n| [[Aysel \u00c7elikel]]<br />(born 1933)||[[Ministry of Justice (Turkey)|Minister of Justice]] (2002)<ref name=\"h\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://arama.hurriyet.com.tr/arsivnews.aspx?id=102190 |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet]] |title=\u00c7elikel: F tipine insani \u00e7\u00f6z\u00fcm |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref>||(''[[Independent politician|independent]]'')\n|-\n|[[G\u00fcldal Ak\u015fit]]<br />(born 1960)||[[Ministry of Culture and Tourism (Turkey)|Minister of Tourism]] (2002\u20132003)<br /> Minister of State (2003\u20132007)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n|-\n| [[Nimet Ba\u015f]]<br />(born 1965)|| Minister of State (2003\u20132007)<br /> [[Ministry of National Education (Turkey)|Minister of National Education]] (2009\u20132011)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n|-\n| [[Selma Aliye Kavaf]]<br />(born 1962)|| Minister of State (2009\u20132011)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n|-\n| [[Fatma \u015eahin]]<br />(born 1966)||[[Ministry of Family, Labour and Social Services (Turkey)|Minister of Family and Social Policies]] (2011\u20132013)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tbmm.gov.tr/develop/owa/milletvekillerimiz_sd.bilgi?p_donem=23&p_sicil=6159 |publisher=TBMM |title=T\u00fcrkiye B\u00fcy\u00fck Millet Meclisi 23. D\u00f6nem Milletvekili-Fatma \u015eahin |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref>||[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n|-\n| [[Ay\u015fenur \u0130slam]]<br />(born 1958)||[[Ministry of Family, Labour and Social Services (Turkey)|Minister of Family and Social Policies]] (2013\u20132015) ||[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n|-\n| [[Ay\u015fen G\u00fcrcan]]<br />(born 1963)||[[Ministry of Family, Labour and Social Services (Turkey)|Minister of Family and Social Policies]] (2015) || (''[[Independent politician|independent]]'')\n|-\n| [[Beril Dedeo\u011flu]]<br />(1961-2019)|| [[Minister of European Union Affairs (Turkey)|Minister of European Union]] (2015) || (''[[Independent politician|independent]]'')\n|-\n| [[Fatma Bet\u00fcl Sayan Kaya]]<br />(born 1981) ||[[Ministry of Family, Labour and Social Services (Turkey)|Minister of Family and Social Policy]] (2016\u20132018 ) ||[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n|-\n| [[J\u00fclide Sar\u0131ero\u011flu]]<br />(born 1979) ||[[Ministry of Family, Labour and Social Services (Turkey)|Minister of Labour and Social Security]] (2017\u20132018) ||[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n|-\n| [[Zehra Z\u00fcmr\u00fct Sel\u00e7uk]]<br />(born 1979) ||[[Ministry of Family, Labour and Social Services (Turkey)|Minister of Family, Labour and Social Services]] (2018\u2013present) ||(''[[Independent politician|independent]]'')\n|-\n| [[Ruhsar Pekcan]]<br />(born 1958) ||[[Ministry of Trade (Turkey)|Minister of Trade]] (2018\u2013present) ||(''[[Independent politician|independent]]'')\n|}\n\n<br />\n\n== Deputy Speakers of the Parliament ==\n[[File:Ay\u015fe_Nur_Bah\u00e7ekap\u0131l\u0131.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Ay\u015fe Nur Bah\u00e7ekap\u0131l\u0131]], [[Deputy Speaker of the Grand National Assembly|Deputy Speaker]] of the Paliament of Turkey]]\nAlthough no woman council president has served in the [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey]] until today, several politicians have served as the [[Deputy Speaker of the Grand National Assembly|Deputy Speaker of the Parliament]] at different times.  In 1972, the first female deputy president of the Republic of Turkey CGP parliamentary deputy has been [[Nermin Neft\u00e7i]]. Some of the other female deputy speakers were [[Meral Ak\u015fener]] (MHP), [[G\u00fcldal Mumcu]] (CHP) and finally [[Ay\u015fe Nur Bah\u00e7ekap\u0131l\u0131]] (AK Party) for a long time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/ilk-kadin-tbmm-baskanvekili-vefat-etti-166476|title=\u0130lk kad\u0131n TBMM ba\u015fkanvekili vefat etti|website=www.hurriyet.com.tr|accessdate=Apr 30, 2020}}</ref> <ref>[http://www.tbmm.gov.tr/develop/owa/milletvekillerimiz_sd.sonuc?p_donem=24&adi=Meral&soyadi=Ak%FEener&il=&parti=&kelime= Parliament page/Meral Ak\u015fener {{in lang|tr}}]</ref> <ref>[http://www.tbmm.gov.tr/develop/owa/milletvekillerimiz_sd.sonuc?p_donem=24&adi=G%FCldal&soyadi=&il=&parti=&kelime= Parliament page/\u015e\u00fckran G\u00fcldal Mumcu {{in lang|tr}}]</ref>\n\n==Party leaders==\n[[File:Meral Ak\u015fener \u0130Y\u0130 Party (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Meral Ak\u015fener]], Leader of [[\u0130yi Party|Good Party]]]]\n\nFirst female [[List of political parties in Turkey|Turkish party leader]] was [[Behice Boran]] (1910\u20131987). A member of the [[Workers Party of Turkey]] (T\u0130P), she was elected as the chairman of the party in 1970 and continued in this post until all the political parties were closed following the [[1980 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat|September 11, 1980 military coup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://t24.com.tr/haber/behice-boran-23-olum-yildonumunde-aniliyor/104098|title=T24 online newspaper|accessdate=Apr 30, 2020}}</ref> Other female party leaders were:\n\n* [[M\u00fcbeccel G\u00f6ktuna]]  (1915\u20131999) [[National Women's Party of Turkey]] (TUKP) (1972\u20131981)\n* [[Rah\u015fan Ecevit]] (1923-2020), [[Democratic Left Party (Turkey)|Democratic Left Party]] (DSP) (1985\u20131987), [[Democratic Left People's Party]] (DSHP) (2010)\n* [[Tansu \u00c7iller]] (born 1946) [[True Path Party]] (DYP) (1993\u20132002), ''([[Prime Minister of Turkey|'''Prime Minister''']] from 1993 to 1996)''\n* [[Nesrin Nas]] (1958), [[Motherland Party (Turkey)|Motherland Party]] (ANAP) (2003\u20132004)\n* [[Filiz Ko\u00e7ali]] (born 1958), [[Socialist Democracy Party]] (2004\u20132009)\n* [[G\u00fcltan K\u0131\u015fanak]] (born 1961), [[Peace and Democracy Party]] (BDP) (2011\u20132014)\n* [[Figen Y\u00fcksekda\u011f]] (born 1971), [[Peoples' Democratic Party (Turkey)]] (2012\u20132017) As of 2014, she is the co-leader of the party.\n* [[Emine \u00dclker Tarhan]] (born 1963), [[Anatolia Party]] (2014\u20132015) As of 2014, she is the founder and leader of the party.\n*[[Fatma Benal Yazgan]] (born 1947), [[Women's Party (Turkey)]] (2014-present)\n* [[Meral Ak\u015fener]] (born 1956), [[Good Party]] (2017\u2013present) co-founder and leader\n\n=== Women's parties ===\nTwo parties were founded by women: [[National Women's Party of Turkey]] in 1972 (up to 1980)  and [[Women's Party (Turkey)]] in 2014\n\n== Parliamentary group vice chairwomen ==\nAccording to the [[Constitution of Turkey|Turkish constitution]], each party with over twenty seats forms a [[parliamentary group]] and each group is represented by 1\u20133 group vice chairpersons ({{lang-tr|grup ba\u015fkanvekili}}) who are authorized to represent, in general terms, the relevant party in the parliament both in relation to the parliament administration and in relations with other party groups, as well as presiding the parliamentary group in the absence of the party president. The first female group vice chairperson in Turkish parliament was [[Oya Arasl\u0131]] of the [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|Republican People's Party]] between 1996 and 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/politika/chpye_12_yil_sonra_kadin_grup_baskanvekili-1054505/|title=CHP'ye 12 y\u0131l sonra kad\u0131n grup ba\u015fkanvekili|website=Radikal|accessdate=Apr 30, 2020}}</ref> Later, there were two parliamentary group chairwomen in parliament: [[Emine \u00dclker Tarhan]] of the Republican People's Party and [[Pervin Buldan]] of the [[Peace and Democracy Party]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.milliyet.com.tr/siyaset/meclisteki-kadin-yonetcilerden-cagri-1426949|title=Meclisteki kad\u0131n y\u00f6netcilerden \u00e7a\u011fr\u0131|website=Milliyet|accessdate=Apr 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Members of Parliament ==\n[[File:First female MPs of the Turkish Parliament (1935).jpg|thumb|The first female MPs Republic of Turkey (1935).<br />'''Top row (left to right):''' [[Mebrure G\u00f6nen\u00e7]] (Afyon), [[Hat\u0131 \u00c7\u0131rpan]] (Ankara), [[T\u00fcrkan \u00d6rs Ba\u015ftu\u011f]] (Antalya), [[Sabiha G\u00f6k\u00e7\u00fcl Erbay]] (Bal\u0131kesir), [[\u015eekibe \u0130nsel]] (Bursa), [[Hatice \u00d6zgener]] (\u00c7ank\u0131r\u0131)<br />'''Middle row (left to right):''' [[Huriye Baha \u00d6niz]] (Diyarbak\u0131r), [[Fatma \u015eakir Memik]] (Edirne), [[Nakiye Elg\u00fcn]] (Erzurum), [[Fakihe \u00d6ymen]] (Ankara), [[Benal Nevzat \u0130star Ar\u0131man]] (\u0130zmir), [[Ferruh G\u00fcpg\u00fcp]] (Kayseri)<br />'''Bottom row (left to right):''' [[Bahire Bedi\u015f Morova Aydilek]] (Konya), [[Mihri Pekta\u015f]] (Malatya), [[Meliha Ula\u015f]] (Samsun), [[Fatma Esma Nayman]] (Seyhan), [[Hatice Sabiha G\u00f6rkey]] (Sivas), [[Seniha Naf\u0131z H\u0131zal]] (Trabzon)]]\n[[File:Sati Kadin at the rostrum of TBMM.jpg|thumb|[[Ankara]] deputy Hat\u0131 \u00c7\u0131rpan at the rostrum of [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey|Parliament of Turkey]].]]The first female MPs of the Turkish Parliament, elected with the 8 February [[1935 Turkish general election|1935 general elections]].\n\n===1935\u20131999 elections===\nFollowing the promising 1935 start, however, the number of women in the parliament began to decrease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/mecliste-kadinin-adi-yine-yok-109330|title=Meclis'te kad\u0131n\u0131n ad\u0131 yine yok|website=www.hurriyet.com.tr|accessdate=Apr 30, 2020}}</ref>Especially in the 1950 and 1961 elections, only 3 women were able to enter the parliament, and since history has been given women the right to vote and be elected, it has been the least women entered into parliament.\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n! Election year\n! No of deputy\n! No of woman MP\n! Woman MP rate\n|-\n|[[1935 Turkish general election|1935]]||395||18||'''%4,6''' \n|-\n|[[1939 Turkish general election|1939]]||429||15||'''%3,7''' \n|-\n|[[1943 Turkish general election|1943]]||435||16||'''%3,7''' \n|-\n|[[1946 Turkish general election|1946]]||465||9||'''%1,9''' \n|-\n|[[1950 Turkish general election|1950]]||487||3||'''%0,6''' \n|-\n|[[1954 Turkish general election|1954]]||541||4||'''%0,7''' \n|-\n|[[1957 Turkish general election|1957]]||610||8||'''%1,3''' \n|-\n|[[1961 Turkish general election|1961]]||450||3||'''%0,7''' \n|-\n|[[1965 Turkish general election|1965]]||450||8||'''%1,8''' \n|-\n|[[1969 Turkish general election|1969]]||450||5||'''%1,1''' \n|-\n|[[1973 Turkish general election|1973]]||450||6||'''%1,3''' \n|-\n|[[1977 Turkish general election|1977]]||450||4||'''%0,9''' \n|-\n|[[1983 Turkish general election|1983]]||399||12||'''%3,0''' \n|-\n|[[1987 Turkish general election|1987]]||450||6||'''%1,3''' \n|-\n|[[1991 Turkish general election|1991]]||450||8||'''%1,8''' \n|-\n|[[1995 Turkish general election|1995]]||550||13||'''%2,4'''\n|-\n|[1999 T\u00fcrkiye genel se\u00e7imleri|[[1999 Turkish general election|1999]]||550||22||'''%4,2''' \n|}\n\n===2002\u2013present elections===\nSince 1995, the number of women in the parliament has been continually on the rise. The 1935 percentage of women, the first year that women were able to be elected to parliament, was surpassed no earlier than in 1999.<ref>[http://www.aku.edu.tr/aku/dosyayonetimi/sosyalbilens/dergi/VI1/aarslan.pdf An Afyon University paper by D. Ali Aslan {{in lang|tr}}]</ref> However, the female representation rate did not fall below 10 percent after the 2007 elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/tr/politika/kadin-milletvekillerinin-temsil-orani-artti/1189573#|title=|accessdate=|date=|work=|publisher=}}</ref>\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n! Election year\n! No of deputy\n! No of woman MP\n! Woman MP rate\n|-\n|[[2002 Turkish general election|2002]]||550||24||'''%4,4 \n|-\n|[[2007 Turkish general election|2007]]||550||50||'''%9,1''' \n|-\n|[[2011 Turkish general election|2011]]||550||79||'''%14,3''' \n|-\n|[[June 2015 Turkish general election|2015<br />''June'']]||550||97||'''%17,6 \n|-\n|[[November 2015 Turkish general election|2015<br />''November'']]||550||81||'''%14,7''' \n|-\n|[[2018 Turkish parliamentary election|2018]]||600||103||'''%17,1'''\n|}\n\n===Members of the Senate (1961-1980)===\nThe [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey]] had a [[Senate of the Republic (Turkey)|Senate]] (upper house) between 1961 and 1980. The following women were elected as the senators: \n* Mebrure Aksoley (1902\u20131984), [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|Republican People's Party]] (CHP) (1964\u20131973)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tbmm.gov.tr/tutanaklar/TUTANAK/CS__/t05/c031/b036/cs__050310360777.pdf |publisher=TBMM |title=Tutanak C. Senatosu B: 36 18.1.1966 O:1|language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref>\n* [[Fatma Hikmet \u0130\u015fmen]], (1918\u20132006), [[Workers Party of Turkey]] (T\u0130P) (1966\u20131975)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.milliyet.com.tr/2006/05/18/ombudsman/okur03.html |newspaper=Milliyet |title=T\u0130P'li Fatma \u0130\u015fmen'in \u00f6l\u00fcm\u00fc |date=2006-05-18 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref>\n* [[Bahriye \u00dc\u00e7ok]] (1919\u20131990), State President's contingency (1971\u20131976).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tbmm.gov.tr/tutanaklar/TUTANAK/CS__/t14/c022/b053/cs__140220530021.pdf |publisher=TBMM |title=C. Senatosu B: 53 29.4.1975 O: 1 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref> The only assassinated woman politician.\n*[[Nermin Abadan Unat]] (born 1921), State President's contingency (1978\u20131980) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.biyografi.net/kisiayrinti.asp?kisiid=1147|title=biyografi.net: Nermin Abadan Unat biyografisi burada \u00fcnl\u00fclerin biyografileri burada|website=www.biyografi.net|accessdate=Apr 30, 2020}}</ref>\n* Aysel Baykal (1939\u20132003), Republican People's Party (CHP) (1979\u20131980)<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.tbmm.gov.tr/tutanaklar/TUTANAK/CS__/t18/c043/cs__18043082.pdf |publisher=TBMM |journal=Cumhuriyet Senatosu Tutanak Dergisi |title=82nci Birle\u015fim |date=23 Oct 1979 |volume=13 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref>\n\n== Governor ==\n[[File:Vali Lale Aytaman 1991 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Lale Aytaman]] is first female [[Governor (Turkey)|Governor]] of Turkey.]]\nTurkey's first female [[Governor (Turkey)|governor]] [[Lale Aytaman]].  Aytaman, who served as the governor of [[Mu\u011fla Province|Mu\u011fla]] between 1991-1995, was appointed to this position by President [[Turgut \u00d6zal]].  Meanwhile, Turkey's first female district governor is \u00d6zlem Bozkurt Gevrek. She served in the [[Orta]] district of [[\u00c7ank\u0131r\u0131 Province|\u00c7ank\u0131r\u0131]] in 1995. After these years, the number of female governors and district governors increased rapidly.<ref>https://www.kpssguncelbilgi.com/mesleklerine-gore-ilk-turk-kadinlari/</ref>\n\n== Local governments ==\nThe first female [[Muhtar (title)|muhtar]] ([[village head]]) in [[Turkey]] was [[G\u00fclk\u0131z \u00dcrb\u00fcl]], who became the muhtar of [[Karpuzlu|Demircidere]] village (now Karpuzlu) in the [[\u00c7ine]] district of [[Ayd\u0131n Province]] in 1933. In the elections, she ran against seven male candidates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.milliyet.com.tr/turkiye-nin-ilk-kadin-muhtari/Blog/?BlogNo=369342|title=T\u00fcrkiye\u2019nin ilk kad\u0131n muhtar\u0131/Tarih/milliyet blog|website=blog.milliyet.com.tr|accessdate=Apr 30, 2020}}</ref> The first female city mayor was [[M\u00fcfide \u0130lhan]], who was elected as the mayor of [[Mersin]] in 1950.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Women in Turkey]]\n* [[Timeline of first women's suffrage in majority-Muslim countries]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Women in national government}}\n\n[[Category:Turkish women in politics]]\n[[Category:Members of the Grand National Assembly of Turkey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Women in Turkey}}\n\n[[Women in Turkey]] have an active participation in national politics, and the number of women in the [[Turkish parliament]] has been increasing steadily in recent elections.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Hat\u0131 \u00c7\u0131rpan.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Hat\u0131 \u00c7\u0131rpan]], one of the first women in the Parliament of Turkey, 1935.]]\nThe [[Republic of Turkey]] was founded on the ashes of the [[Ottoman Empire]] on 29 October 1923. Although the political power of some [[Valide Sultan]]s (queen mothers) over the [[Ottoman Sultans]] was considerable, especially during the era known as the [[Sultanate of Women]], women had no chance to serve in any official political post in the Ottoman era.\n\nOne notable female political activist in the first days of the Republican era was [[Nezihe Muhittin]], who founded the first women's party in Turkey in June 1923; however, it was never legalized because the Republic was not officially declared yet. [[Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]], the founder of the Republic initiated a [[Atat\u00fcrk's Reforms|series of reforms]] to modernize the country, including civil and political equality for women for the first time. On 17 February 1926, Turkey adopted a new [[Turkish civil code (1926)|civil code]] by which the rights of Turkish women and men were declared equal except in suffrage.<ref>Sina Ak\u015fin:''K\u0131sa T\u00fcrkiye Tarihi'', T\u00fcrkiye \u0130\u015f bankas\u0131 K\u00fclt\u00fcr yay\u0131nlar\u0131,\u0130stanbul,2011,{{ISBN|978-9944-88-172-2}} p.188.</ref> After a short but intense struggle, Turkish women achieved voting rights in local elections by Act no. 1580 on 3 April 1930.<ref name=\"tempo\">''T\u00fcrkiye'nin 75 y\u0131l\u0131'' , Tempo Yay\u0131nc\u0131l\u0131k, \u0130stanbul, 1998, p.48,59,250</ref> Four years later, through legislation enacted on 5 December 1934, they gained full universal suffrage, earlier than most other countries.<ref name=\"tempo\"/>\n\n== President ==\nUp to the present, there have been no female [[President of Turkey|Presidents]] in Turkey.\n\n== Speakers of Parliament ==\nUp to the present, there have been no female [[Speaker of the Grand National Assembly|Speakers of Grand National Assembly]] in Turkey.\n\n== Vice President ==\nUp to the present, there have been no female [[Vice President of Turkey|Vice Presidents]] in Turkey.\n\nVice President office established in Turkey in 2018.\n\n== Prime Minister (1923-2018) ==\n[[File:(Tansu \u00c7iller) Rueda de prensa de Felipe Gonz\u00e1lez y la primera ministra de Turqu\u00eda. Pool Moncloa. 16 de noviembre de 1995 (cropped).jpeg|thumb|upright|[[Tansu \u00c7iller]] is first and only female [[Prime Minister of Turkey|Prime Minister]] of [[Turkey]].]]\n[[Tansu \u00c7iller]], a career professor of economics since 1983, entered politics in November 1990, joining the conservative [[True Path Party]] (DYP). On June 13, 1993, she was elected the party's leader, and on 25 June the same year, \u00c7iller was appointed the [[Prime Minister of Turkey|Prime Minister]] of a coalition government, becoming Turkey's first and only female prime minister to date. She served at this post until 6 March 1996.\n\nPrime Minister office abolished in Turkey in 2018.\n\n==Government ministers==\nThe first female Turkish [[Cabinet of Turkey|government minister]] was [[T\u00fcrk\u00e2n Akyol]], in 1971. She was the [[Ministry of Health (Turkey)|Minister of Health]] in [[Nihat Erim]]'s technocratic government.<ref name=\"75 y\u0131l\">''T\u00fcrkiye'nin 75 y\u0131l\u0131'', H\u00fcrg\u00fc\u00e7 Gazetecilik,, \u0130stanbul,1998</ref><ref name=\"h\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/16508594_p.asp |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet]] |title=Erkek egemen T\u00fcrkiye |date=2010-12-11 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref> In 1983, she was one of the founders of [[SODEP]], short for Social Democracy Party, a new party which went on to become one of the major political parties of Turkey in 1980s.\n\nFemale government ministers up to the present are as follows:\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!Name\n!Ministry\n!Party\n|-\n|[[T\u00fcrk\u00e2n Akyol]]<br />(1928\u20132017)||[[Ministry of Health (Turkey)|Minister of Health and Social Security]] (1971)<ref name=\"75 y\u0131l\"/><br />Minister of State (Family) 1992\u20131993|| (''[[Independent politician|independent]]'')<br />[[Social Democratic Populist Party (Turkey)|SHP]]\n|-\n|[[Nermin Neft\u00e7i]]<br />(1924\u20132003)||[[Ministry of Culture and Tourism (Turkey)|Minister of Culture]] (1974\u20131975)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[Republican Reliance Party|CGP]]\n|-\n|[[\u0130mren Aykut]]<br />(born 1940)||[[Ministry of Family, Labour and Social Services (Turkey)|Minister of Labour and Social Security]] (1987\u20131991)<br /> Minister of State (1991 and 1996),<br />[[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)|Minister of Environment]] (1997\u20131999)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/ekonomi/19847923.asp |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet]] |title=Eski \u00c7al\u0131\u015fma Bakan\u0131\u2019n\u0131 bile \u2018ye\u015fil kart testi\u2019ne \u00e7a\u011f\u0131rd\u0131lar |author=Babacan, Nuray |date=2012-02-06 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref>||[[Motherland Party (Turkey)|ANAP]]\n|-\n| [[G\u00fcler \u0130leri]]<br />(born 1948)|| Minister of State (1991\u20131993)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[Social Democratic Populist Party (Turkey)|SHP]]\n|-\n| [[Aysel Baykal]]<br />(1939\u20132003)|| Minister of State (1995\u20131995)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tbmm.gov.tr/hukumetler/HB50.htm |publisher=TBMM |title=I. \u00c7iller H\u00fck\u00fcmeti Bakanlar Kurulu 25.06.1993\u201305.10.1995 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref>||[[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|CHP]]\n|-\n| [[\u00d6nay Alpago]]<br />(born 1947)|| Minister of State (1994\u20131995)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[Social Democratic Populist Party (Turkey)|SHP]]\n|-\n| [[I\u015f\u0131lay Sayg\u0131n]]<br />(1947-2019)|| Minister of State (1995\u20131996)<br /> [[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)|Minister of Environment]] (1996),<br /> [[Ministry of Culture and Tourism (Turkey)|Minister of Tourism]] (1996)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[True Path Party|DYP]]\n|-\n| [[Ayfer Y\u0131lmaz]]<br />(born 1956)|| Minister of State (1996\u20131997)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[True Path Party|DYP]]\n|-\n| [[Tansu \u00c7iller]]<br />(born 1946)||[[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] (1996\u20131997)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[True Path Party|DYP]]\n|-\n| [[Meral Ak\u015fener]]<br />(born 1956)||[[Ministry of the Interior (Turkey)|Minister of Interior]] (1996\u20131997)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[True Path Party|DYP]]\n|-\n| [[Tayyibe G\u00fclek]]<br />(born 1968)|| Minister of State (1999\u20132002)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[Democratic Left Party (Turkey)|DSP]]\n|-\n| [[Melda Bayer]]<br />(born 1950)|| Minister of State (1999\u20132002)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[Democratic Left Party (Turkey)|DSP]]\n|-\n| [[Aysel \u00c7elikel]]<br />(born 1933)||[[Ministry of Justice (Turkey)|Minister of Justice]] (2002)<ref name=\"h\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://arama.hurriyet.com.tr/arsivnews.aspx?id=102190 |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet]] |title=\u00c7elikel: F tipine insani \u00e7\u00f6z\u00fcm |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref>||(''[[Independent politician|independent]]'')\n|-\n|[[G\u00fcldal Ak\u015fit]]<br />(born 1960)||[[Ministry of Culture and Tourism (Turkey)|Minister of Tourism]] (2002\u20132003)<br /> Minister of State (2003\u20132007)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n|-\n| [[Nimet Ba\u015f]]<br />(born 1965)|| Minister of State (2003\u20132007)<br /> [[Ministry of National Education (Turkey)|Minister of National Education]] (2009\u20132011)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n|-\n| [[Selma Aliye Kavaf]]<br />(born 1962)|| Minister of State (2009\u20132011)<ref name=\"h\"/>||[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n|-\n| [[Fatma \u015eahin]]<br />(born 1966)||[[Ministry of Family, Labour and Social Services (Turkey)|Minister of Family and Social Policies]] (2011\u20132013)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tbmm.gov.tr/develop/owa/milletvekillerimiz_sd.bilgi?p_donem=23&p_sicil=6159 |publisher=TBMM |title=T\u00fcrkiye B\u00fcy\u00fck Millet Meclisi 23. D\u00f6nem Milletvekili-Fatma \u015eahin |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref>||[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n|-\n| [[Ay\u015fenur \u0130slam]]<br />(born 1958)||[[Ministry of Family, Labour and Social Services (Turkey)|Minister of Family and Social Policies]] (2013\u20132015) ||[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n|-\n| [[Ay\u015fen G\u00fcrcan]]<br />(born 1963)||[[Ministry of Family, Labour and Social Services (Turkey)|Minister of Family and Social Policies]] (2015) || (''[[Independent politician|independent]]'')\n|-\n| [[Beril Dedeo\u011flu]]<br />(1961-2019)|| [[Minister of European Union Affairs (Turkey)|Minister of European Union]] (2015) || (''[[Independent politician|independent]]'')\n|-\n| [[Fatma Bet\u00fcl Sayan Kaya]]<br />(born 1981) ||[[Ministry of Family, Labour and Social Services (Turkey)|Minister of Family and Social Policy]] (2016\u20132018 ) ||[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n|-\n| [[J\u00fclide Sar\u0131ero\u011flu]]<br />(born 1979) ||[[Ministry of Family, Labour and Social Services (Turkey)|Minister of Labour and Social Security]] (2017\u20132018) ||[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n|-\n| [[Zehra Z\u00fcmr\u00fct Sel\u00e7uk]]<br />(born 1979) ||[[Ministry of Family, Labour and Social Services (Turkey)|Minister of Family, Labour and Social Services]] (2018\u2013present) ||(''[[Independent politician|independent]]'')\n|-\n| [[Ruhsar Pekcan]]<br />(born 1958) ||[[Ministry of Trade (Turkey)|Minister of Trade]] (2018\u2013present) ||(''[[Independent politician|independent]]'')\n|}\n\n<br />\n\n== Deputy Speakers of the Parliament ==\n[[File:Ay\u015fe_Nur_Bah\u00e7ekap\u0131l\u0131.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Ay\u015fe Nur Bah\u00e7ekap\u0131l\u0131]], [[Deputy Speaker of the Grand National Assembly|Deputy Speaker]] of the Paliament of Turkey]]\nAlthough no woman council president has served in the [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey]] until today, several politicians have served as the [[Deputy Speaker of the Grand National Assembly|Deputy Speaker of the Parliament]] at different times.  In 1972, the first female deputy president of the Republic of Turkey CGP parliamentary deputy has been [[Nermin Neft\u00e7i]]. Some of the other female deputy speakers were [[Meral Ak\u015fener]] (MHP), [[G\u00fcldal Mumcu]] (CHP) and finally [[Ay\u015fe Nur Bah\u00e7ekap\u0131l\u0131]] (AK Party) for a long time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/ilk-kadin-tbmm-baskanvekili-vefat-etti-166476|title=\u0130lk kad\u0131n TBMM ba\u015fkanvekili vefat etti|website=www.hurriyet.com.tr|accessdate=Apr 30, 2020}}</ref> <ref>[http://www.tbmm.gov.tr/develop/owa/milletvekillerimiz_sd.sonuc?p_donem=24&adi=Meral&soyadi=Ak%FEener&il=&parti=&kelime= Parliament page/Meral Ak\u015fener {{in lang|tr}}]</ref> <ref>[http://www.tbmm.gov.tr/develop/owa/milletvekillerimiz_sd.sonuc?p_donem=24&adi=G%FCldal&soyadi=&il=&parti=&kelime= Parliament page/\u015e\u00fckran G\u00fcldal Mumcu {{in lang|tr}}]</ref>\n\n==Party leaders==\n[[File:Meral Ak\u015fener \u0130Y\u0130 Party (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Meral Ak\u015fener]], Leader of [[\u0130yi Party|Good Party]]]]\n\nFirst female [[List of political parties in Turkey|Turkish party leader]] was [[Behice Boran]] (1910\u20131987). A member of the [[Workers Party of Turkey]] (T\u0130P), she was elected as the chairman of the party in 1970 and continued in this post until all the political parties were closed following the [[1980 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat|September 11, 1980 military coup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://t24.com.tr/haber/behice-boran-23-olum-yildonumunde-aniliyor/104098|title=T24 online newspaper|accessdate=Apr 30, 2020}}</ref> Other female party leaders were:\n\n* [[M\u00fcbeccel G\u00f6ktuna]]  (1915\u20131999) [[National Women's Party of Turkey]] (TUKP) (1972\u20131981)\n* [[Rah\u015fan Ecevit]] (1923-2020), [[Democratic Left Party (Turkey)|Democratic Left Party]] (DSP) (1985\u20131987), [[Democratic Left People's Party]] (DSHP) (2010)\n* [[Tansu \u00c7iller]] (born 1946) [[True Path Party]] (DYP) (1993\u20132002), ''([[Prime Minister of Turkey|'''Prime Minister''']] from 1993 to 1996)''\n* [[Nesrin Nas]] (1958), [[Motherland Party (Turkey)|Motherland Party]] (ANAP) (2003\u20132004)\n* [[Filiz Ko\u00e7ali]] (born 1958), [[Socialist Democracy Party]] (2004\u20132009)\n* [[G\u00fcltan K\u0131\u015fanak]] (born 1961), [[Peace and Democracy Party]] (BDP) (2011\u20132014)\n* [[Figen Y\u00fcksekda\u011f]] (born 1971), [[Peoples' Democratic Party (Turkey)]] (2012\u20132017) As of 2014, she is the co-leader of the party.\n* [[Emine \u00dclker Tarhan]] (born 1963), [[Anatolia Party]] (2014\u20132015) As of 2014, she is the founder and leader of the party.\n*[[Fatma Benal Yazgan]] (born 1947), [[Women's Party (Turkey)]] (2014-present)\n* [[Meral Ak\u015fener]] (born 1956), [[Good Party]] (2017\u2013present) co-founder and leader\n\n=== Women's parties ===\nTwo parties were founded by women: [[National Women's Party of Turkey]] in 1972 (up to 1980)  and [[Women's Party (Turkey)]] in 2014\n\n== Parliamentary group vice chairwomen ==\nAccording to the [[Constitution of Turkey|Turkish constitution]], each party with over twenty seats forms a [[parliamentary group]] and each group is represented by 1\u20133 group vice chairpersons ({{lang-tr|grup ba\u015fkanvekili}}) who are authorized to represent, in general terms, the relevant party in the parliament both in relation to the parliament administration and in relations with other party groups, as well as presiding the parliamentary group in the absence of the party president. The first female group vice chairperson in Turkish parliament was [[Oya Arasl\u0131]] of the [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|Republican People's Party]] between 1996 and 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/politika/chpye_12_yil_sonra_kadin_grup_baskanvekili-1054505/|title=CHP'ye 12 y\u0131l sonra kad\u0131n grup ba\u015fkanvekili|website=Radikal|accessdate=Apr 30, 2020}}</ref> Later, there were two parliamentary group chairwomen in parliament: [[Emine \u00dclker Tarhan]] of the Republican People's Party and [[Pervin Buldan]] of the [[Peace and Democracy Party]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.milliyet.com.tr/siyaset/meclisteki-kadin-yonetcilerden-cagri-1426949|title=Meclisteki kad\u0131n y\u00f6netcilerden \u00e7a\u011fr\u0131|website=Milliyet|accessdate=Apr 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Members of Parliament ==\n[[File:First female MPs of the Turkish Parliament (1935).jpg|thumb|The first female MPs Republic of Turkey (1935).<br />'''Top row (left to right):''' [[Mebrure G\u00f6nen\u00e7]] (Afyon), [[Hat\u0131 \u00c7\u0131rpan]] (Ankara), [[T\u00fcrkan \u00d6rs Ba\u015ftu\u011f]] (Antalya), [[Sabiha G\u00f6k\u00e7\u00fcl Erbay]] (Bal\u0131kesir), [[\u015eekibe \u0130nsel]] (Bursa), [[Hatice \u00d6zgener]] (\u00c7ank\u0131r\u0131)<br />'''Middle row (left to right):''' [[Huriye Baha \u00d6niz]] (Diyarbak\u0131r), [[Fatma \u015eakir Memik]] (Edirne), [[Nakiye Elg\u00fcn]] (Erzurum), [[Fakihe \u00d6ymen]] (Ankara), [[Benal Nevzat \u0130star Ar\u0131man]] (\u0130zmir), [[Ferruh G\u00fcpg\u00fcp]] (Kayseri)<br />'''Bottom row (left to right):''' [[Bahire Bedi\u015f Morova Aydilek]] (Konya), [[Mihri Pekta\u015f]] (Malatya), [[Meliha Ula\u015f]] (Samsun), [[Fatma Esma Nayman]] (Seyhan), [[Hatice Sabiha G\u00f6rkey]] (Sivas), [[Seniha Naf\u0131z H\u0131zal]] (Trabzon)]]\n[[File:Sati Kadin at the rostrum of TBMM.jpg|thumb|[[Ankara]] deputy Hat\u0131 \u00c7\u0131rpan at the rostrum of [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey|Parliament of Turkey]].]]The first female MPs of the Turkish Parliament, elected with the 8 February [[1935 Turkish general election|1935 general elections]].\n\n===1935\u20131999 elections===\nFollowing the promising 1935 start, however, the number of women in the parliament began to decrease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/mecliste-kadinin-adi-yine-yok-109330|title=Meclis'te kad\u0131n\u0131n ad\u0131 yine yok|website=www.hurriyet.com.tr|accessdate=Apr 30, 2020}}</ref>Especially in the 1950 and 1961 elections, only 3 women were able to enter the parliament, and since history has been given women the right to vote and be elected, it has been the least women entered into parliament.\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n! Election year\n! No of deputy\n! No of woman MP\n! Woman MP rate\n|-\n|[[1935 Turkish general election|1935]]||395||18||'''%4,6''' \n|-\n|[[1939 Turkish general election|1939]]||429||15||'''%3,7''' \n|-\n|[[1943 Turkish general election|1943]]||435||16||'''%3,7''' \n|-\n|[[1946 Turkish general election|1946]]||465||9||'''%1,9''' \n|-\n|[[1950 Turkish general election|1950]]||487||3||'''%0,6''' \n|-\n|[[1954 Turkish general election|1954]]||541||4||'''%0,7''' \n|-\n|[[1957 Turkish general election|1957]]||610||8||'''%1,3''' \n|-\n|[[1961 Turkish general election|1961]]||450||3||'''%0,7''' \n|-\n|[[1965 Turkish general election|1965]]||450||8||'''%1,8''' \n|-\n|[[1969 Turkish general election|1969]]||450||5||'''%1,1''' \n|-\n|[[1973 Turkish general election|1973]]||450||6||'''%1,3''' \n|-\n|[[1977 Turkish general election|1977]]||450||4||'''%0,9''' \n|-\n|[[1983 Turkish general election|1983]]||399||12||'''%3,0''' \n|-\n|[[1987 Turkish general election|1987]]||450||6||'''%1,3''' \n|-\n|[[1991 Turkish general election|1991]]||450||8||'''%1,8''' \n|-\n|[[1995 Turkish general election|1995]]||550||13||'''%2,4'''\n|-\n|[1999 T\u00fcrkiye genel se\u00e7imleri|[[1999 Turkish general election|1999]]||550||22||'''%4,2''' \n|}\n\n===2002\u2013present elections===\nSince 1995, the number of women in the parliament has been continually on the rise. The 1935 percentage of women, the first year that women were able to be elected to parliament, was surpassed no earlier than in 1999.<ref>[http://www.aku.edu.tr/aku/dosyayonetimi/sosyalbilens/dergi/VI1/aarslan.pdf An Afyon University paper by D. Ali Aslan {{in lang|tr}}]</ref> However, the female representation rate did not fall below 10 percent after the 2007 elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/tr/politika/kadin-milletvekillerinin-temsil-orani-artti/1189573#|title=|accessdate=|date=|work=|publisher=}}</ref>\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n! Election year\n! No of deputy\n! No of woman MP\n! Woman MP rate\n|-\n|[[2002 Turkish general election|2002]]||550||24||'''%4,4 \n|-\n|[[2007 Turkish general election|2007]]||550||50||'''%9,1''' \n|-\n|[[2011 Turkish general election|2011]]||550||79||'''%14,3''' \n|-\n|[[June 2015 Turkish general election|2015<br />''June'']]||550||97||'''%17,6 \n|-\n|[[November 2015 Turkish general election|2015<br />''November'']]||550||81||'''%14,7''' \n|-\n|[[2018 Turkish parliamentary election|2018]]||600||103||'''%17,1'''\n|}\n\n===Members of the Senate (1961-1980)===\nThe [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey]] had a [[Senate of the Republic (Turkey)|Senate]] (upper house) between 1961 and 1980. The following women were elected as the senators: \n* Mebrure Aksoley (1902\u20131984), [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|Republican People's Party]] (CHP) (1964\u20131973)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tbmm.gov.tr/tutanaklar/TUTANAK/CS__/t05/c031/b036/cs__050310360777.pdf |publisher=TBMM |title=Tutanak C. Senatosu B: 36 18.1.1966 O:1|language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref>\n* [[Fatma Hikmet \u0130\u015fmen]], (1918\u20132006), [[Workers Party of Turkey]] (T\u0130P) (1966\u20131975)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.milliyet.com.tr/2006/05/18/ombudsman/okur03.html |newspaper=Milliyet |title=T\u0130P'li Fatma \u0130\u015fmen'in \u00f6l\u00fcm\u00fc |date=2006-05-18 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref>\n* [[Bahriye \u00dc\u00e7ok]] (1919\u20131990), State President's contingency (1971\u20131976).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tbmm.gov.tr/tutanaklar/TUTANAK/CS__/t14/c022/b053/cs__140220530021.pdf |publisher=TBMM |title=C. Senatosu B: 53 29.4.1975 O: 1 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref> The only assassinated woman politician.\n*[[Nermin Abadan Unat]] (born 1921), State President's contingency (1978\u20131980) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.biyografi.net/kisiayrinti.asp?kisiid=1147|title=biyografi.net:\u00a0Nermin Abadan\u00a0Unat biyografisi burada \u00a0\u00fcnl\u00fclerin biyografileri burada|website=www.biyografi.net|accessdate=Apr 30, 2020}}</ref>\n* Aysel Baykal (1939\u20132003), Republican People's Party (CHP) (1979\u20131980)<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.tbmm.gov.tr/tutanaklar/TUTANAK/CS__/t18/c043/cs__18043082.pdf |publisher=TBMM |journal=Cumhuriyet Senatosu Tutanak Dergisi |title=82nci Birle\u015fim |date=23 Oct 1979 |volume=13 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-02-02 }}</ref>\n\n== Governor ==\n[[File:Vali Lale Aytaman 1991 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Lale Aytaman]] is first female [[Governor (Turkey)|Governor]] of Turkey.]]\nTurkey's first female [[Governor (Turkey)|governor]] [[Lale Aytaman]].  Aytaman, who served as the governor of [[Mu\u011fla Province|Mu\u011fla]] between 1991-1995, was appointed to this position by President [[Turgut \u00d6zal]].  Meanwhile, Turkey's first female district governor is \u00d6zlem Bozkurt Gevrek. She served in the [[Orta]] district of [[\u00c7ank\u0131r\u0131 Province|\u00c7ank\u0131r\u0131]] in 1995. After these years, the number of female governors and district governors increased rapidly.<ref>https://www.kpssguncelbilgi.com/mesleklerine-gore-ilk-turk-kadinlari/</ref>\n\n== Local governments ==\nThe first female [[Muhtar (title)|muhtar]] ([[village head]]) in [[Turkey]] was [[G\u00fclk\u0131z \u00dcrb\u00fcl]], who became the muhtar of [[Karpuzlu|Demircidere]] village (now Karpuzlu) in the [[\u00c7ine]] district of [[Ayd\u0131n Province]] in 1933. In the elections, she ran against seven male candidates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.milliyet.com.tr/turkiye-nin-ilk-kadin-muhtari/Blog/?BlogNo=369342|title=T\u00fcrkiye\u2019nin ilk kad\u0131n muhtar\u0131/Tarih/milliyet blog|website=blog.milliyet.com.tr|accessdate=Apr 30, 2020}}</ref> The first female city mayor was [[M\u00fcfide \u0130lhan]], who was elected as the mayor of [[Mersin]] in 1950.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Women in Turkey]]\n* [[Timeline of first women's suffrage in majority-Muslim countries]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Women in national government}}\n\n[[Category:Turkish women in politics]]\n[[Category:Members of the Grand National Assembly of Turkey]]\n", "name_user": "Trappist the monk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMembers of the Senate (1961-1980):remove 'invisible' characters from cs1|2 template parameters; (3\u00d7 NBSP; 1\u00d7 extra space)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Women_in_Turkish_politics"}
